cally different from those conceived by their founders and creators in the capital city. Migdal proposes an answer to this paradox: a model of state-society relations that highlights the state's struggle with other social organizations and a theory that explains the differing abilities of states to predominate in those struggles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSocial control. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aArab Socialist Union (ASU).  aArabs of Palestine.  aBaer, Gabriel.  aBaker, Raymond William.  aCardew, Frederic.  aCartwright, John R.  aClapham, Chistopher.  aDekmejian, R. Hrair.  aFrance.  aFree Officers (Egypt).  aGandhi, Indira.  aGurr, Tedd Robert.  aHansen, Roger D.  aHistadrut (General Federation of Labor).  aHorowitz, Dan.  aIran.  aIraq.  aJabotinsky, Vladimir.  aJordan.  aKup, A. P.  aLebanon.  aLittle, K. L.  aMexico.  aMigdal, Joel S.  aNasser, Gamal Abdul.  aOttoman Empire.  aRobinson, Ronald.  aSabri, Ali.  aShapiro, Yonathan.  aUnited States.  aWaterbury, John.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691212852zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691212852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691212852.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK